WEBVTT

00:00:00.102 --> 00:00:03.200
A green checkmark feels comforting in
software.

00:00:03.633 --> 00:00:08.581
It says: the build passed. The tests
passed. The

00:00:08.594 --> 00:00:12.448
robot is happy. And when you are tired, it
is easy

00:00:12.474 --> 00:00:15.938
to read that as a bigger sentence: This is
safe

00:00:15.964 --> 00:00:19.167
to merge. But a green check usually means

00:00:19.193 --> 00:00:22.956
something narrower. It means: this check
passed, on

00:00:22.982 --> 00:00:26.302
this version, under these conditions. That
is

00:00:26.328 --> 00:00:29.544
useful evidence. It is not a verdict.

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:33.800
Use three questions to keep the
signal in its lane:

00:00:34.341 --> 00:00:37.141
Fresh base. Right diff.

00:00:38.052 --> 00:00:39.250
Uncovered risk.

00:00:40.274 --> 00:00:44.650
First: Fresh base. Did the check run
against the target you are about to

00:00:44.650 --> 00:00:47.300
merge or deploy into?

00:00:47.300 --> 00:00:50.224
In a fast-moving repo, the target branch
can move

00:00:50.224 --> 00:00:53.297
while a pull request waits. The check may
have

00:00:53.323 --> 00:00:56.656
been true when main looked one way. Then
other

00:00:56.682 --> 00:01:01.162
work lands. The surrounding file changes.

00:01:01.188 --> 00:01:05.700
A validator appears. A slot that was empty
becomes occupied.

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:09.846
The old check is not useless.
But it is dated evidence.

00:01:09.846 --> 00:01:14.900
In one exploratory AI Village
pull-request study,

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:19.925
local git reconstruction covered
six hundred and ten pull requests.

00:01:19.925 --> 00:01:25.680
In one hundred forty-four cases, the head
did not descend from the recorded base.

00:01:25.706 --> 00:01:29.091
That does not prove those branches
were unsafe.

00:01:29.117 --> 00:01:32.594
It does mean the base relationship was
a useful place to look.

00:01:32.594 --> 00:01:37.138
Green on an old base is not bad evidence.
It is old evidence.

00:01:38.162 --> 00:01:41.630
Second: Right diff. Did the check
inspect the

00:01:41.654 --> 00:01:45.339
exact change that will land?
A file list is not

00:01:45.365 --> 00:01:48.737
the same as today's merge diff. A preview
from

00:01:48.763 --> 00:01:52.000
memory is not the same as today's merge
diff.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.195
In the same study's case appendix,
one pull request

00:01:55.195 --> 00:01:59.000
was described as mechanically
mergeable, with passing checks.

00:01:59.388 --> 00:02:04.440
A reviewer noted a narrower problem. The
diff inserted new entries before an

00:02:04.466 --> 00:02:08.112
already-merged tail. That shifted the
intended

00:02:08.138 --> 00:02:11.849
numbering. It did not append after current
main.

00:02:12.774 --> 00:02:15.925
Parsing was not the whole issue. The real

00:02:15.938 --> 00:02:19.323
question was this. Did the checked change
match

00:02:19.349 --> 00:02:22.867
the review question? So do not only ask
whether a

00:02:22.900 --> 00:02:26.706
check passed. Ask what diff the check was
attached to.

00:02:27.746 --> 00:02:31.459
Third: Uncovered risk. What important
failure

00:02:31.485 --> 00:02:34.688
could still happen if the check is right?
Some

00:02:34.714 --> 00:02:38.555
failures are easy for automation to see.
The file

00:02:38.582 --> 00:02:43.516
does not compile. The unit test fails.
A required

00:02:43.542 --> 00:02:47.123
command exits with an error. Other
failures are

00:02:47.149 --> 00:02:51.576
about meaning. Did this remove recent
work?

00:02:51.602 --> 00:02:55.027
Did the app still get the layout
it expects? Did it

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:58.022
change permissions, ordering, user-visible
wording,

00:02:58.217 --> 00:03:01.602
or a hidden invariant? The most useful
question

00:03:01.615 --> 00:03:04.185
is not, "Did the robot approve?" It is,

00:03:04.185 --> 00:03:07.345
"What would still worry me if the robot
is right?"

00:03:08.371 --> 00:03:12.240
This is also the caveat. A stale branch is
not

00:03:12.266 --> 00:03:16.095
automatically unsafe. A large deletion
count is

00:03:16.121 --> 00:03:19.897
not automatically bad. And a passing check
is not

00:03:19.923 --> 00:03:24.597
automatically enough. Each of those is a
signal, not a verdict.

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:28.650
Before treating a green check as approval,
ask:

00:03:28.850 --> 00:03:34.200
Fresh base: did the check run against the
target I am about to merge or deploy into?

00:03:34.627 --> 00:03:38.038
Right diff: did it inspect the exact
change that will land?

00:03:38.950 --> 00:03:41.250
Uncovered risk: what important failure

00:03:41.250 --> 00:03:44.150
could still happen if this check
is correct?

00:03:44.350 --> 00:03:47.200
If you are using an AI assistant during
review,

00:03:47.302 --> 00:03:51.200
ask it the same thing: What version,
base branch, and diff

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:56.000
did this check run on? What files,
behaviors, or risks did it not inspect?

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.744
What human decision remains
if the check is correct?

00:04:01.757 --> 00:04:05.000
That prompt cannot make the decision safe.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:06.900
But it can slow the moment down

00:04:06.900 --> 00:04:08.650
so the evidence stays visible.

00:04:09.115 --> 00:04:13.883
Keep the green check. It is useful.
Just read it like a receipt.

00:04:13.909 --> 00:04:18.297
What version did it check?
What diff did it inspect?

00:04:18.323 --> 00:04:21.812
What risk did it leave uncovered?

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:24.911
Let the green check speed up the review.

00:04:24.924 --> 00:04:28.349
Do not let it replace the question.
